---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="NIST Framework: Building a Comprehensive Security Program | Sheepdog" description="Implement the NIST Cybersecurity Framework to structure your security program. Learn core functions and how to apply NIST." showMatrix={true}>
  <section>
    <h1>NIST Framework: Building a Comprehensive Security Program</h1>
    <p class="lead">The NIST Cybersecurity Framework provides a structured approach to building security programs. It's used by organizations worldwide and often required for compliance. Here's how to implement it.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What is NIST?</h2>
    <p>NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology) CSF is a voluntary framework for managing cybersecurity risk:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Developed in collaboration with industry and government</li>
      <li>Provides common language for security</li>
      <li>Helps organizations identify and prioritize security investments</li>
      <li>Works for organizations of all sizes and industries</li>
      <li>Increasingly required by regulations and contracts</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Five Core Functions</h2>
    
    <h3>Identify</h3>
    <p>Understand your business, resources, and risks:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Inventory of assets (hardware, software, data)</li>
      <li>Business processes and dependencies</li>
      <li>Threat and vulnerability assessment</li>
      <li>Regulatory requirements</li>
      <li>Risk assessment and prioritization</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Protect</h3>
    <p>Implement controls to prevent attacks:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Access control and authentication</li>
      <li>Data protection and encryption</li>
      <li>Security awareness training</li>
      <li>Maintenance and patching</li>
      <li>Technical and physical security controls</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Detect</h3>
    <p>Monitor for security incidents:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Security monitoring and logging</li>
      <li>Intrusion detection and malware detection</li>
      <li>Incident response procedures</li>
      <li>Security assessments and testing</li>
      <li>Anomaly detection and alerting</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Respond</h3>
    <p>Contain and remediate incidents:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Incident response plan</li>
      <li>Communication during incidents</li>
      <li>Containment and eradication</li>
      <li>Evidence preservation</li>
      <li>Forensic analysis</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Recover</h3>
    <p>Restore systems to normal operation:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Disaster recovery and business continuity</li>
      <li>Backup and recovery procedures</li>
      <li>System restoration</li>
      <li>Data restoration</li>
      <li>Recovery testing</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>22 Categories and 23 Subcategories</h2>
    <p>Each function has categories with specific controls:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Identify:</strong> Asset Management, Business Environment, Governance, Risk Assessment, Risk Management Strategy</li>
      <li><strong>Protect:</strong> Access Control, Awareness & Training, Data Security, Information & Processes, Protective Technology</li>
      <li><strong>Detect:</strong> Anomalies & Events, Security Continuous Monitoring, Detection Processes</li>
      <li><strong>Respond:</strong> Response Planning, Communications, Analysis, Mitigation, Improvements</li>
      <li><strong>Recover:</strong> Planning, Improvements, Communications, Recovery Planning</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Implementing NIST in Your Organization</h2>
    
    <h3>Step 1: Executive Support</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Leadership commitment to security</li>
      <li>Budget and resources allocation</li>
      <li>Organizational changes to support security</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Step 2: Assess Current State</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Identify which NIST functions and categories apply</li>
      <li>Document current controls and gaps</li>
      <li>Prioritize gaps by risk</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Step 3: Develop Implementation Plan</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Short-term fixes (quick wins)</li>
      <li>Medium-term improvements (6-12 months)</li>
      <li>Long-term transformation (1-3 years)</li>
      <li>Budget and resource allocation</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Step 4: Implement Controls</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Identify and data protection</li>
      <li>Build detective and response capabilities</li>
      <li>Develop disaster recovery capability</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Step 5: Measure and Report</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Track progress against NIST framework</li>
      <li>Regular reporting to leadership</li>
      <li>Continuous improvement based on maturity</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>NIST vs Regulatory Frameworks</h2>
    
    <h3>NIST vs ISO 27001</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>NIST: US-focused, framework approach, flexible</li>
      <li>ISO: International standard, certified by auditors, specific controls</li>
      <li>Many organizations use both</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>NIST vs CIS Controls</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>NIST: Comprehensive framework, all organization types</li>
      <li>CIS: Specific, prioritized controls, easier to implement</li>
      <li>Can use NIST for structure, CIS for specific controls</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>NIST in Regulated Industries</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Healthcare (HIPAA):</strong> Often aligned with NIST</li>
      <li><strong>Finance (PCI, Bank Secrecy):</strong> Equivalent to NIST</li>
      <li><strong>Government (FEDERAL):</strong> NIST is baseline</li>
      <li><strong>Critical Infrastructure:</strong> NIST is primary framework</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Common NIST Implementation Mistakes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Treating it as a compliance checkbox rather than strategy</li>
      <li>Implementing everything instead of prioritizing risk</li>
      <li>Lack of executive support and funding</li>
      <li>Not measuring progress and results</li>
      <li>Failing to update framework as threats evolve</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Tools & Frameworks for NIST Implementation</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>NIST CSF Mapping Tools:</strong> Online tools to map controls to NIST categories</li>
      <li><strong>NIST 800 Series:</strong> Detailed guidance documents for specific areas</li>
      <li><strong>NIST Cybersecurity Framework 2.0:</strong> Updated version with new guidance</li>
      <li><strong>Consulting services:</strong> Help with assessment and implementation</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Measuring NIST Maturity</h2>
    <p>NIST framework levels:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Partial (Level 1):</strong> Ad hoc, reactive approach</li>
      <li><strong>Risk-Informed (Level 2):</strong> Processes defined but not formal</li>
      <li><strong>Repeatable (Level 3):</strong> Documented processes, consistent execution</li>
      <li><strong>Adaptive (Level 4):</strong> Continuous improvement, automated controls</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="cta">
    <h2>Build Your NIST-Based Program</h2>
    <p>Sheepdog Cyber Defense helps Texas organizations implement NIST Cybersecurity Framework and assess maturity through penetration testing.</p>
    <a href="/contact" class="btn">Start Your NIST Implementation</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

